Alex Churchill
Car Accidents by Location and Severity, Seattle
Effectiveness, Expressiveness, Context

I chose to plot 2023 Seattle car accidents by location and severity using a Folium cluster plot with a filter. The chart starts zoomed out, so the viewer and can see the whole area covered and get an idea of total accidents. Viewers can then zoom in on different parts of the city they are interested in to get an idea of where accidents are occurring and the relative frequency between areas. At this stage, a viewer may also want to filter by the severity of the accident, which can be accessed in the top right corner of the chart. Changing the filter can give a viewer an idea of how often different severity levels occur and where. Finally, zooming into an individual cluster a viewer can see the exact location where accidents occurred. This level is also useful for identifying potentially dangerous intersections. The viewer will also see icons encoded by design and color. The colors are organized by severity. Dark red and skull indicate fatal crash, light red and hospital indicate severe injuries, orange with crutch indicates light injuries, green with car crash indicates property damage, and gray means the results of the crash are unknown. These are easy to distinguish and imply a scale for severity for each category except unknown, which does not logically fit on the scale. Finally, a tooltip shows the severity as well as the address so viewers can look up locations of interest on google maps or further research a particular accident. Overall, this chart is effective because it conveys geographic and quantitative information about car accidents on a macro and micro scale, and expressive because it accurately displays the location of accident clusters and individual accidents.
